[1] WHO alert
Date: Thu 28 Aug 2014
Source: The Wall Street Journal [edited]
http://online.wsj.com/articles/who-warns-ebola-outbreak-could-hit-20-000-within-nine-months-1409226146


The World Health Organization (WHO) warned [Thu 28 Aug 2014] that the number of people affected by Ebola virus [disease; EVD] could rise to 20 000 within the next 9 months and a projected half a billion dollars would be needed to fund efforts aimed at stopping the spread of the disease. In a document released Thu [28 Aug 2014], the UN health body said the outbreak of the disease "continues to accelerate." More than 40 percent of reported cases have occurred within the last 3 weeks, the report said.

As of [26 Aug 2014 -- see WHO update of 28 Aug 2014], health authorities in the 4 affected nations -- Guinea, Liberia, Nigeria, and Sierra Leone -- have reported 3069 cases of the disease since the outbreak started in December [2013]. The disease, a virus that causes a fever so high it punctures blood vessels to cause internal bleeding, has already killed 1552 people.

WHO Assistant Director General Bruce Aylward was at a press briefing on WHO's strategy to combat EVD at the United Nations headquarters in Geneva on Thu [28 Aug 2014].

The Geneva-based WHO said in its report, which it dubbed a road map for responding to EVD, strengthening laboratory facilities and adding staff with more expertise in the disease were necessary to containing the outbreak. Public health infrastructure needed to be improved to cope with future threats. The road map assumes "that in many areas of intense transmission the actual number of cases may be 4-fold higher than currently reported." The road map called for the establishment of EVD isolation centers and burials of victims which are supervised by health care experts, among other specific responses to the disease.

The WHO said getting health experts to regions affected by the EVD outbreak was an urgent priority. That has been made difficult because international airlines, including Air France, British Airways and Emirates Airline, have suspended flights to some of the 4 affected countries. Air traffic into the affected areas was likely to be addressed in the next 2 weeks, the WHO said. By the end of September [2014], a United Nations-led plan will be launched to improve air access to the area, it added.

The WHO program will likely cost around USD 490 million and require contributions from national governments, some UN and non-governmental agencies, as well as humanitarian organizations, it said. Funding for the budget hasn't yet been completed, according to a WHO spokeswoman, who wasn't able to provide details of the amount of money still needed. [more]

[Byline: Neil Maclucas, Gbenga Akingbule]

