******
[2] Nigeria: new case(s)
Date: Thu 28 Aug 2014
Source: Reuters [edited]
http://in.reuters.com/article/2014/08/28/health-ebola-nigeria-idINKBN0GS0S520140828


A doctor in Nigeria's oil industry hub of Port Harcourt has died from Ebola [virus disease], after he was infected by a man linked to the 1st case in Africa's most populous country, the Health Ministry said on Thu [28 Aug 2014]. Heath Ministry spokesman Dan Nwomeh said on his Twitter feed that the doctor had treated a primary contact of Patrick Sawyer, the Liberian who brought EVD to Lagos. His death brings the number of EVD fatalities in Nigeria to 6. The total number of recorded cases had risen by 2 to 15, Nwomeh said, the other one being the wife of the doctor who is showing EVD symptoms and whose test results are awaited.

Port Harcourt lies at the heart of Nigeria's 2 million barrels per day oil industry, Africa's biggest, and is a hub for expatriate workers in major international oil companies. Nwomeh said 70 contacts of the doctor were now under surveillance in Port Harcourt. It was not immediately clear what impact the arrival of EVD would have on oil operations. The major [companies] operating in Nigeria have historically been comfortable with a fair degree of risk in the-oil producing Niger Delta, including attacks on oil installations and rampant kidnapping of expatriates.

The news came 2 days after Health Minister Onyebuchi Chukwu said authorities had "thus far contained" the EVD outbreak in Africa's largest economy, with only one case left being treated in an isolation ward in Lagos. All Nigerian cases have been direct or indirect contacts of Sawyer, who collapsed on arrival at Lagos airport from Liberia on [22 Jul 2014] and later died, but was treated before anyone knew what he had.

[By an unfortunate coincidence, the Centre for Gas, Refining and Petrochemicals (CGRP) ... is holding an international conference and exhibition from 27-28 Aug 2014 [today] in Port Harcourt. http://businessdayonline.com/2014/08/cgrp-world-bank-hold-conference-on-petroleum-gas-refining/#.U_81tjK3OTI. I hope the 650 participants, many from overseas, will watch their temperatures for 21 days after they return home, bearing in mind that although they may not have touched a sick person, they could have touched a surface contaminated by a case in the conference hall or hotel. Remember the Hong Kong hotel where a SARS super-spreader contaminated several men on the same floor? - Mod.JW]

